<br>
If Iris were a follower of Tunare, she would despise anyone who harmed the Mother's avatar or even the creatures of her plane.   As it is, she doesn't think too highly of them, but she might throw them a heal if they were bleeding to death. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ujenscorda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jens Corda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/11/02 2:39:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1709.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Gods and Hunting</span><hr size=1> No religion, based in either the real-world or a wacky fantasy game, is going to have a single philosophy that is adhered to by all its followers. Any free thinking race is going to have disputes over interpreting the will of the divine, often to the point of going to war over minor differences in ideology. <br>
<br>
In the case of Tunare you could have several different groups, each of whom worshipped her, each of whom was convinced they were the only ones privy to the ÅgtruthÅh.<br>
<br>
1) The mellow hippies who commune with the Great Animal Spirits and meditate via herbal pipeweed.<br>
2) The environmental radicals who have a violent grudge with the dwarfs and gnomes whose rape of the earth is anathema to them, and who regularly fight against loggers, trappers and hunters.<br>
3) The survival of the fittest brigade who see life as a struggle to survive with the weak being devoured by the strong. Holding a Nietzschean view of the eco-system they aim to be on top of the food chain.<br>
4) Zen-like spiritualists who believe everything is tied to one life-force that renews itself through reincarnation. They believe that the heads of their order are reborn as white hawks, thus the most sacred of animals, yadda, yadda...<br>
5) Etc, etc. <br>
<br>
I donÅft think youÅfll find Tunare coming down to her followers with a copy of the EQ rule book saying ÅgYou see THIS is what IÅfm all about.Åh<br>
<br>
Her followers are free to interpret her will as they see fit. If a lone wacko decides his (or her) beliefs call for her death then heÅfs got his own brand-new branch of Tunarism and if heÅfs charismatic enough heÅfs even likely to convince others to follow him.<br>
<br>
Those who wish to stick only to the &quot;approved&quot; EQ mythos regarding the Gods could call their chars Fundamentalists and seek out the heretics and blasphemers for an ingame inquisition. Whatever butters your biscuit but there's a lot of rp'ing potential in the EQ pantheon of Gods that generally goes unused.<br>
<br>
